;*************************
;*************************
;*************************
;*************************

@NODE introduction "Introduction"

MiniMail is the result of a few months of pretty hard work.  Despite being 
good, it still isn't even a fraction of what I want it to be.  This is 
mainly because of a fixed deadline, set as a result of doing MiniMail as a 
"extended essay" at school.

MiniMail is simply an integrated email system - it lets you read and write 
email, without the fuzz of having to rely on external mailers, pop-clients,
etc.  It was designed to be very user friendly, letting you concentrate on 
reading and writing your email rather than fuzzing around with a fancy but 
slow and complex product.

@ENDNODE

;*************************
;*************************
;*************************
;*************************

@NODE features "Features"

· Quick, smooth, and easy to use.  No superfluous GUI engine, like MUI, 
  is used.

· Quick installation (and deinstallation).

· Lets you read and write mail both online and offline.

· Built-in POP3 and SMTP clients (for getting and sending mail).

· Capability to automatically check for new mail at regular intervals 
  (@{" autoival " link configautoival}).

· Support for an @{" alias list " link config 40} (user database), with 
  groups.

· Lets you send mail to many recipients at the same time.

· Reads and understands complex MIME messages (file attachments, ...).

· Iconification via Commodity, and an optional AppIcon/AppMenuItem.

· Locale support (for both languages and timezones).

· Complies with most related RFCs (for example 821, 822, 1225 and 1521).

· Can work as an external mailer together with for example browsers 
  (@{" argument " link usagearg}).

· More...

@ENDNODE

;*************************
;*************************
;*************************
;*************************

@NODE install "How to install"

MiniMail requires:

- AmigaOS 2.0 (3.0 or better recommended)

- An installed copy of AmiTCP version 3+ or Mlink
  (aminet:comm/tcp/AmiTCP-demo-40.lha)
  (aminet:comm/net/mlink132.lha)

- reqtools.library version 38 or better
  (aminet:util/libs/ReqToolsUsr.lha)

Minimail is very easy to install and deinstall; simply extract the archive
to wherever you want it (no assigns have to be made).  
Load MiniMail.config.example into a texteditor, make the necessary changes
(see @{" configuration " link config}) and then save it back as 
MiniMail.config.

If you use {b}Mlink{ub}, make sure that the environment variable HOSTNAME has been
set to reflect your hostname. This is usually what's after the @ in your
email address. For example, entering "setenv HOSTNAME lls.se" in a shell
sets the variable to "lls.se", which is the appropriate hostname for me.
If you don't set this variable, MiniMail won't let you write mails.

@ENDNODE

;*************************
;*************************
;*************************
;*************************

@NODE config "Configuration"

@{U}@{B}Minimail.config@{UB}@{UU}
The configuration is kept in a plaintext file (MiniMail.config) located in 
the same drawer as the executable (MiniMail).  @{" Here " link configex} is
an example.  If you want to, you can just modify the included file 
MiniMail.config.example to suit your needs, and then rename it as 
MiniMail.config.

Lines starting with a semicolon (;) are ignored, allowing comments to be 
made.

(The bold text is the default value.)

@{" mailserver       " link configmailserver} @{B}none@{UB} 
@{" autoival         " link configautoival} @{B}120@{UB}
@{" username         " link configusername} @{B}none@{UB}
@{" password         " link configpassword} @{B}none@{UB}
@{" delmail          " link configdelmail} @{B}no@{UB}
@{" allmail          " link configallmail} @{B}no@{UB}
@{" deffrom          " link configdeffrom} @{B}none@{UB}
@{" deforganization  " link configdeforganization} @{B}none@{UB}
@{" editor           " link configeditor} @{B}none@{UB}
@{" pubscreen        " link configpubscreen} @{B}default public screen@{UB}
@{" window           " link configwindow} @{B}visible portion of the screen@{UB}
@{" keepopen         " link configkeepopen} @{B}no@{UB}
@{" mainfont         " link configmainfont} @{B}screen's font@{UB}
@{" listfont         " link configlistfont} @{B}screen's font@{UB}
@{" headerfont       " link configheaderfont} @{B}screen's font@{UB}
@{" bodyfont         " link configbodyfont} @{B}screen's font@{UB}
@{" cx_popup         " link configcx_popup} @{B}yes@{UB}
@{" cx_hotkey        " link configcx_hotkey} @{B}rawkey ramiga return@{UB}
@{" appmenu          " link configappmenu} @{B}auto@{UB}
@{" appicon          " link configappicon} @{B}auto@{UB}
@{" appiconxy        " link configappiconxy} @{B}any@{UB}
@{" timezone         " link configtimezone} @{B}locale's timezone@{UB}
@{" charset          " link configcharset} @{B}ISO-8859-1@{UB}
@{" textfile         " link configtextfile} @{B}RAM:MiniMail.post@{UB}
@{" tempfile         " link configtempfile} @{B}ProgDir:Minimail_tempfile@{UB}
@{" defsaved         " link configdefsaved} @{B}ProgDir:Saved/@{UB}
@{" defdecoded       " link configdefdecoded} @{B}ProgDir:Decoded/@{UB}

@{" Config example " link configex}

@{U}@{B}Minimail.aliases@{UB}@{UU}
The alias list feature can be used to set up a list of aliases, 
corresponding to one or several email addresses and/or other aliases.  
@{" Here " link "userdbex"} is an example of an alias list.

Each line in the alias list file (ProgDir:MiniMail.aliases) consists of an 
alias, followed by one or several email addresses or aliases.  
This means that it's possible to create groups.  (See the example.)

All aliases entered into any of the header window's To:, Cc: or Bcc: fields 
will be resolved as soon as you press enter, or just before the mail is sent.

(Note that for historical reasons, the file ProgDir:MiniMail.users will also
be checked if ProgDir:MiniMail.aliases doesn't exist.)

@{" Alias list example " link userdbex}

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE userdbex "Config - alias list"
@TOC config

volley      volley@lls.se (Pelle Claesson)
ein         pontus.sjostrom@mailbox.swipnet.se (Pontus Sjöström)
erik        e.andersson@lostander.gu.se
unts        unts@louder.bzmbzm.ch
theend      volley, ein, erik, logog@worldmoc.hc
all         theend, unts

(When entering "theend" in a @{" To: " link usageheaderftw}, @{" Cc: " link usageheaderftw} or @{" Bcc: " link usageheaderftw} field, 
it will be expanded into "volley@lls.se (Pelle Claesson), pontus.sjostrom@mailbox.swipnet.se (Pontus Sjöström), 
e.andersson@lostander.gu.se, logog@worldmoc.hc, unts@louder.bzmbzm.ch".)

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configmailserver "Config - mailserver"
@TOC config

@{B}mailserver@{UB} <hostname>
    The mailserver to use.   This is usually the last part of your email 
    address; for example, my email address is volley@lls.se, and my mail-
    server is lls.se.   If you're uncertain of what to put, please ask your
    internet provider!

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configautoival "Config - autoival"
@TOC config

@{B}autoival@{UB} [<seconds>]
    MiniMail is capable of automatically looking for new mail at regular
    intervals.  Autoival tells MiniMail how often, and if at all, these 
    checks are to be made.  If you want no automatic checks at all, 
    include the keyword, but leave the argument out.
    The default is 120 seconds.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configusername "Config - username"
@TOC config

@{B}username@{UB} <username>
    Set this to your username, which is usually what you type in when your
    provider asks you for your "login".  
    For example, my username is "volley".  No default is provided.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configpassword "Config - password"
@TOC config

@{B}password@{UB} <password>
    A password is required in order to be able to get mail.  
    It's generally the same as the password you're asked for after you send
    the provider your username (login).  If you specify no password here, 
    you'll be asked for one at the first getmail attempt.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configdelmail "Config - delmail"
@TOC config

@{B}delmail@{UB} [yes|NO]
    If enabled, MiniMail will try to delete all successfully retrieved mail
    from the server.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configallmail "Config - allmail"
@TOC config

@{B}allmail@{UB} [yes|NO]
    If enabled, MiniMail will get ALL mail from the server at each session
    (instead of only getting new mail).  Useful together with delmail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configdeffrom "Config - deffrom"
@TOC config

@{B}deffrom@{UB} <from>
    This is the default from-field body, or in other words, your email 
    address and real name.  
    The recommended format is "my@email.adr (Real Name)" 
    (not including the quotes).  
    For example, I have "volley@lls.se (Pelle Claesson)" as deffrom.
    No default is provided.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configdeforganization "Config - deforganization"
@TOC config

@{B}deforganization@{UB} <organization>
    If you're part of a specific group or organization, 
    you can type it in here.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configeditor "Config - editor"
@TOC config

@{B}editor@{UB} <editor>
    MiniMail has no built-in text editor, and so, you have to specify a 
    commandline for an external editor here.  Replace the filename with %s 
    (a percent sign followed by a lowercase s).  Make sure the editor 
    doesn't detach (for example, if you're using CygnusED, you would specify
    something like "ced %s -keepio").  No default is provided, but "ed %s" 
    should work on most Amigas.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configpubscreen "Config - pubscreen"
@TOC config

@{B}pubscreen@{UB} <screenname>
    Specifies the name of the public screen to open on, unless the default 
    public screen is to be used.  If the screen you specify here doesn't 
    exist, MiniMail will create it.  The displaymode of the current default 
    public screen will be used.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configwindow "Config - window"
@TOC config

@{B}window@{UB} [left][/[top][/[width][/[height]]]]
    Lets you specify the initial dimensions of the main window.  
    For example, window //320/100 will make it 320 pixels wide and 100 
    pixels tall.  Defaults to the visible portion of the screen when first 
    opened, then it defaults to the dimensions the window had before it was
    last closed.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configkeepopen "Config - keepopen"
@TOC config

@{B}keepopen@{UB} [yes|NO]
    Determines the behaviour of the mainwindow when composing a mail.
      Yes causes it to remain open while compising a mail.
      No causes it to close while composing a mail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configmainfont "Config - mainfont"
@TOC config

@{B}mainfont@{UB} <fontname> <fontheight>
    Specifies the main font to use, for gadgets and the like.  
    Proportional fonts are allowed.  Defaults to the screen's font.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configlistfont "Config - listfont"
@TOC config

@{B}listfont@{UB} <fontname> <fontheight>
    Specifies the font to use for the mail list.  
    Proportional fonts are allowed.  Defaults to the screen's font.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configheaderfont "Config - headerfont"
@TOC config

@{B}headerfont@{UB} <fontname> <fontheight>
    Specifies the font to use for the mail header.  
    Proportional fonts are allowed.  Defaults to the screen's font.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configbodyfont "Config - bodyfont"
@TOC config

@{B}bodyfont@{UB} <fontname> <fontheight>
    Specifies the font to use for the mail body.  
    Proportional fonts are allowed.  Defaults to the screen's font.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configcx_popup "Config - cx_popup"
@TOC config

@{B}cx_popup@{UB} [YES|both|net|none]
    Determines if the main window, the net window, both of them, or 
    none of them, are to be opened at startup.  Defaults to yes (that is, 
    the main window will be opened at startup).

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configcx_hotkey "Config - cx_hotkey"
@TOC config

@{B}cx_hotkey@{UB} <hotkey>
    The popup hotkey to use.  Defaults to "rawkey ramiga return".  
    Press it to open the main window.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configappicon "Config - appicon"
@TOC config

@{B}appicon@{UB} [yes|AUTO|no]
    Defines the behaviour of the AppIcon.  
      Yes makes it permanent.
      No keeps it disabled at all times.
      Auto makes it appear only when the main window is iconified.  
      To deiconify, you can doubleclick on the icon.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configappmenu "Config - appmenu"
@TOC config

@{B}appmenu@{UB} [yes|AUTO|no]
    Defines the behaviour of the AppMenuItem.  
      Yes makes it permanent.
      No keeps it disabled at all times.
      Auto makes it appear only when the main window is iconified.  
      To deiconify, you can select the menu item.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configappiconxy "Config - appiconxy"
@TOC config

@{B}appiconxy@{UB} <x> <y>
    Specifies the position of the AppIcon.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configdefreplyto "Config - defreplyto"
@TOC config

@{B}defreplyto@{UB} <reply-to>
    This is the default reply-to field body.  If you want replies to your 
    mails to be sent to a different address than the one in the from-field,
    you can specify that here.  Most people won't use this.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configtimezone "Config - timezone"
@TOC config

@{B}timezone@{UB} (+|-)hh00
    This must be used if MiniMail can't obtain the correct timezone from 
    your system.  GMT is +0000 hours; if you live "west" of the GMT, 
    specify a negative amount of hours, and if you live "east" of the GMT,
    specify a positive amount.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configcharset "Config - charset"
@TOC config

@{B}charset@{UB} [<charset>]
    Let's you specify which charset to use when creating a mail.  
    The default is ISO-8859-1 (common in Europe).  You might want to use 
    for example US-ASCII, if you live in the States.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configtextfile "Config - textfile"
@TOC config

@{B}textfile@{UB} <filename>
    Lets you specify the file Minimail will use to compose new mail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configtempfile "Config - tempfile"
@TOC config

@{B}tempfile@{UB} <filename>
    Lets you specify the file that will be used as a spoolfile when getting
    mails larger than 10 Kb.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configdefsaved "Config - defsaved"
@TOC config

@{B}defsaved@{UB} <filename>
    Lets you specify the default directory to use when saving mails.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configdefdecoded " Config - defdecoded"
@TOC config

@{B}defdecoded@{UB} <filename>
    Lets you specify the default directory to use when decoding MIME parts.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE configex "Config - example"
@TOC config

mailserver      lls.se
autoival        90

username        volley
password        foobar
delmail         no
allmail         no

deffrom         user@host.se (Real Name)
deforganization	My organization or group

editor          ced %s -keepio

pubscreen       Workbench
mainfont        topaz.font 8
listfont        topaz.font 8
headerfont      topaz.font 8
bodyfont        topaz.font 8

cx_popup        no
cx_hotkey       rawkey ramiga return
appicon         auto
appmenu         yes
appiconxy       100 100

timezone        +0100

@ENDNODE

;*************************
;*************************
;*************************
;*************************

@NODE usage "Usage"

The main window is always in one of two modes: @{B}mails mode@{UB} or 
@{B}list mode@{UB}.


In @{B}list mode@{UB}, it consists of a list of mails, and the following 
gadgets (one or more rows) at the top.

@{"Net.." link usagenet} @{"Mails" link usagemails} @{"New.." link usagenew} @{"Inb" link usageinb} @{"Outb" link usageoutb} @{"Hidden" link usagehidden} @{"Hid" link usagehid} @{"Imp" link usageimp} @{"Unr" link usageunr} @{"Del" link usagedel} @{"Quit" link usagequit}



In @{B}mails mode@{UB}, it consist of a header section and a body section, 
and the following gadgets (one or more rows) at the top.

@{"Net.." link usagenet} @{"List" link usagelist} @{"New.." link usagenew} @{"Reply.." link reply} @{"Forw.." link forward} @{" < " link usageprev} @{" > " link usagenext} @{" >| " link usagelast} @{"Hid" link usagehid} @{"Imp" link usageimp} @{"Unr" link usageunr} @{"Del" link usagedel} @{"Hdr" link usagehdr} @{"Quit" link usagequit}



@{" Menus " link usagemenus}

@{" Keyboard shortcuts " link usageshortcuts}


How to @{" compose a new mail " link compose}.

How to @{" reply to a mail " link reply}.

How to @{" forward a mail " link forward}.

How to use @{" arguments " link usagearg} (for use with other programs like WWW browsers).

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagenet "Usage - net window"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - net window@{UB}

The net window can be opened from the main window by clicking on the 
"Net.." gadget.

It contains two gadgets, "Get mail" and "Put mail".  By clicking on one of 
these, you trigger either the POP3-client (mail-getting part of MiniMail) 
or the SMTP-client (mail-putting part of MiniMail).  Only one of the 
clients can run at a single time.

Next to the gadgets, the statuses of both clients are displayed.

Note that MiniMail can get mail automatically at regular intervals (@{" autoival " link configautoival}).  
Sending is also carried out automatically.  Therefore, there's usually 
no need to use any of these gadgets.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagemails "Usage - mails mode"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - mails mode@{UB}

Enter @{" mails mode " link usage} (you can also use the return key to switch 
between the two modes).

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagelist "Usage - list mode"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - list mode@{UB}

Enter @{" list mode " link usage} (you can also use the return key to switch 
between the two modes).

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagenew "Usage - new"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - new@{UB}

To send a new mail, click on "New.." in the main window.  If everything has 
been set up correctly, the editor is loaded.  If you have a signature file 
present (ProgDir:MiniMail.signature), it will be included in the mail.

After saving the text and quitting the editor, the @{" header window " link usageheaderwindow} will be 
brought up.  Please note that if you leave the editor without saving your 
text, MiniMail will assume that you cancelled the mail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usageheaderwindow "Usage - headerwindow"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - headerwindow@{UB}

The header window is used when you're composing a new mail, replying to a 
mail or forwarding a mail.

At the top, it contains two string gadgets, each with an accompanying 
button.  The first string gadget is the "To:" gadget, in which you write 
down the email address(es) and/or the alias(es) of the intended 
recipient(s).  If you have several recipients, separate them with commas.
Use the button next to the string gadget to bring up the @{" from/to subwindow " link usageheaderftw}.  
In the second string gadget, enter the subject of the message.  
The accompanying button can be used to bring up the @{" miscellaneous subwindow " link usageheadermw}.

If you want to attach files to your message, click on the "Attachments.." 
gadget to go to the @{" attachments subwindow " link usageheaderaw}.  
If you want to edit the text again, before proceeding, you can click on 
"Edit.." to bring up the editor again.  When you're done, click on "Done" 
to store the mail.  To cancel it, either close the window, or click on 
"Cancel".

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usageheaderftw "Usage - headerwindow from/to subwindow"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - headerwindow from/to subwindow@{UB}

The from/to subwindow lets you specify more specific information about the 
originator and destination of the mail.  It contains six string gadgets.

@{B}From@{UB} - Specify who the letter is from here.  Note that it's 
                perfectly legal to enter for example a visiting friend's 
                address and/or name here, as long as you enter your own 
                address in the sender field.  It is recommended to specify 
                a default from-field in the config.

@{B}Sender@{UB} - Used to specify a sender, unless the from field above 
                  already contains the same information (which it usually does).

@{B}Reply-To@{UB} - Tells the receiver where to send replies to.  
                    Use with caution.

@{B}To@{UB} - Simply determines the primary recipient(s) of the mail.
              If you want to enter several recipients, separate them with
              commas.

@{B}Cc@{UB} - Secondary recipient(s), who are to be sent "carbon copies" of 
              the mail.

@{B}Blind Cc@{UB} - Almost same as To and Cc, with the only exception that 
                    the receivers won't get to know about each other.

As you might expect, the "Done" gadget saves changes, while "Cancel" 
discards them.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usageheadermw "Usage - headerwindow miscellaneous subwindow"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - headerwindow miscellaneous subwindow@{UB}

The miscellaneous subwindow lets you specify more specific information about
the contents of the mail.

@{I}Subject@{UI} - Simply the subject of the mail.  Please write something 
                   useful in here.

@{I}Keywords@{UI} - Keywords, separated by commas.  (Rarely used feature.)

@{I}Comments@{UI} - Comments.  (Rarely used feature.)

@{I}Organization@{UI} - Your group or organization.

The "Done" gadget saves changes, while "Cancel" discards them.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usageheaderaw "Usage - headerwindow attachments subwindow"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - headerwindow attachments subwindow@{UB}

The attachments subwindow lets you attach files (both binary and textual 
ones) to your mails.

Clicking on "Attach.." brings up a filerequester, that lets you select a 
file to add to the list.  Several files can of course be attached, but 
make sure that it will be possible to hold the whole mail in memory.
To remove a file from the list, select it and click "Detach".  To detach
all files, use "Detach all".

Surprise: click on the "Done" gadget when you're done.  :)

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usageinb "Usage - inb"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - inb@{UB}

Short for inbound.  When selected, causes inbound mails to be shown in the 
list.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usageoutb "Usage - outb"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - outb@{UB}

Short for outbound.  When selected, causes outbound mails to be shown in the
list.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagehidden "Usage - hidden"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - hidden@{UB}

When selected, causes hidden mails to be shown too.  If either @{" Inb " link usageinb} or @{" Outb " link usageoutb} is selected, 
only inbound and/or outbound hidden mails will be shown.  If neither Inb 
nor Out is selected, only hidden mails are shown.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagehid "Usage - hid"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - hid@{UB}

Short for hide.  Marks the currently selected mails as (un)hidden.  Hidden
mails are displayed in italics in the listview (please note that mails yet
to be exported also are shown in italics).

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usageimp "Usage - imp"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - imp@{UB}

Short for important.  Marks the currently selected mails as (un)important.
Important mails are displayed with white foreground text.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagehdr "Usage - hdr"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - hdr@{UB}

When selected, causes the actual header as present in the email to be 
displayed on top of the body.  Please note, that if Hdr is pressed then 
you save the mail, the header will be included in the mail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usageunr "Usage - unr"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - unr@{UB}

Short for unreplied.  Marks the currently selected mails as (un)replied.
All incoming mails are marked as unread.  These are displayed in bold in
the listview.  After having been read once, the mail is marked as unreplied
instead, causing it to be displayed in inverse mode.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagedel "Usage - del"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - del@{UB}

Short for delete.  By @{B}doubleclicking@{UB} on this gadget, the currently
selected or shown mail(s) is/are deleted from the database.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagequit "Usage - quit"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - quit@{UB}

Click on this gadget to quit MiniMail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usageprev "Usage - <"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - <@{UB}

Goes to the previous mail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagenext "Usage - >"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - >@{UB}

Goes to the next mail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagelast "Usage - >|"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - >|@{UB}

Goes to the first unread mail in the database (or to the last one if there 
are no unread ones).

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagearg "Usage - arguments"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - argument@{UB}

You can send an email address as an argument to MiniMail.  If minimail is up
and running, it will be as if you pressed the @{" New.. " link usagenew} button, 
if its not, it will be as if you start minimail and press the 'New..' button.

Some examples:

 AWeb - Setting / Changesettings / Network - External programs / mailto: / 
        command = PATH/minimail / arguments = %s.

 Voyager - Settings / Network / Other / mailto: App. = PATH/minimail %h.

NOTE: PATH = The path were you installed MiniMail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usageshortcuts "Usage - Keyboard shortcuts"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - Keyboard shortcuts@{UB}

@{B}ESC@{UB} - Hides the window.

@{B}Return@{UB} - Jumps between @{" mails mode " link usagemails} and @{" list mode " link usagelist}.

@{B}Cursor up/down@{UB} - Scrolls the mail down/up.  Use with shift to scroll a whole page at a time.

@{B}Cursor left/right@{UB} - Goes to the previous/next mail.  Use shift plus
                             cursor right to go to the next unread mail (or 
                             to the last one, if there're no unread ones).

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE usagemenus "Usage - menus"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - menus@{UB}

@{B}Save to disk..@{UB} - A filerequester is brought up, letting you save 
                          the current mail (as shown in the body section) 
                          or all selected mails (when in list mode) to disk.
                          If you want to include the header in the saved 
                          mail, make sure the @{" Hdr " link usagehdr} 
                          gadget is selected before saving.

@{B}Optimize..@{UB} - Initiates an optimization of the database.  In other 
                      words, all deleted mails are removed from disk.  Do 
                      this once in a while.

@{B}About..@{UB} - Brings up the about-requester.

@{B}Hide@{UB} - Hides the main window (same as using the close gadget and
                pressing the ESC key).

@{B}Quit@{UB} - Terminates MiniMail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE compose "Composing a new mail"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - Composing a new mail" @{UB}

To send a new mail, click on "New.." in the main window.  If everything has
been set up correctly, the editor is loaded.  If you have a signature file 
present (ProgDir:MiniMail.signature), it will be included in the mail.

After saving the text and quitting the editor, the @{" header window " link usageheaderwindow} will be brought up.  
Please note that if you leave the editor without saving your text, MiniMail
will assume that you cancelled the mail.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE reply "Replying to a mail"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - Replying a mail" @{UB}

If you want to reply to a mail you're reading, click on "Reply..".
The editor will be loaded with a text containing a header, the original
mail in quoted form and your signature.

After saving the text and quitting the editor, the @{" header window " link usageheaderwindow} will be brought up.
The From: field from the original message will be copied into the To: gadget.
Also the Subject: field is copied.

@ENDNODE

;*************************

@NODE forward "Forwarding a mail"
@TOC usage
@{B}Usage - Forwarding a mail" @{UB}

If you want to forward a mail you're reading to others, click on "Forward..".
The editor will be loaded with a text containing containing a header, the 
original mail enclosed within begin/end lines, and your signature.

After saving the text and quitting the editor, the @{" header window " link usageheaderwindow} will be brought up.
The Subject: field is copied from the original mail.

@ENDNODE

